text_retweet:
#repost @mercyiaspire with @get_repost
・・・
the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptable” in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe it’s the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers don’t hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. i’m writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like “what did you do that made him beat you”. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

text:
last week, in a statement on gofundme, christine blasey ford thanked those who supported her when she came forward to testify in front of the senate judiciary committee — and the world — that justice brett m. kavanaugh, then a supreme court nominee, sexually assaulted her when they were teenagers. she said speaking out was “terrifying,” but she knew it was her “civic duty.”
•
on her gofundme page, ford reflected on the experience: “i am grateful to have had the opportunity to fulfill my civic duty,” she wrote. “having done so, i am in awe of the many women and men who have written me to share similar life experiences, and now have bravely shared their experience with friends and family, many for the first time. i send you my heartfelt love and support. i wish i could thank each and every one of you individually. thank you.”
•
ford closed her crowdfunding account, which raised nearly $650,000, on wednesday, saying the donations have been a “godsend.” she said that the money “allowed us to take reasonable steps to protect ourselves against frightening threats,” including paying for security services for her family and her, as well as a home security system. (ford’s attorney said ford had been receiving death threats.) she added that any unused donations will be given to organizations that support survivors of trauma. (photo by win mcnamee / getty; illustration by @thelilynews)

text:
11/30/2017 — the assault 🚨
.
if there’s one thing men have learned about themselves in the #metoo movement, it’s that we are a profoundly broken gender.
.
of course there are good ones of us out there — read: those of us who haven’t ascended to the highest corridors of power after either bragging about sexual assault on tape and/or having a petulant meltdown in front of the us senate after being credibly accused of rape — but this moment in history has helped us men realize that we have a lot of behavior and blind spots to answer for.
.
one shortcoming i’ve learned to watch for in my own education as a cis hetero man is the tendency to overlook same-gender assault. we guys do not have an “assaulting women” problem, but an assault problem at large.
.
these are my personal, very biased thoughts as we land on the 1-year anniversary of the @bostonglobe first reporting on bryon hefner’s sexual assault, a scandal that rocked beacon hill, enveloping the state senate, the lgbtqa community and trump-era politics into one perfect storm.
.
the story isn’t all that different from the ones we’ve heard before. hefner (left), the spouse of then-massachusetts senate president stanley rosenberg (right), abused his proximity to power to intimidate other men, touch them and talk to them inappropriately, and then threaten them into silence.
.
thankfully, at least four of the brave souls hefner had the stones to abuse came forward. 4 months later, he ended up indicted on multiple charges of sexual assault, criminal lewdness, and distributing nude photographs without consent. today, hefner faces a possible 2 years in a county jail and up to 5 years in state prison.
.
facing the public storm, rosenberg resigned from the presidency that december and then from the senate altogether in may 2018 when it came to light that he had given hefner access to his email account and may have known his husband to be a predatory actor. in fairness, that much remains under investigation and the couple has been separated since earlier this year.
.
the morals of the story are clear, at least for me. if you see something, say something. believe survivors. and know that you are not alone.

text: yesterday i worked on a set with an actor who randomly brought up his opinion that “women are falsely accusing men of raping them and so they can get their money...all these basketball players and football players...and men don’t even want to hire women anymore and i don’t blame them. they’re afraid if they make a little joke like “ohh look at my peepee” they’re gonna get in trouble. if this had happened in frank sinatra or marlon brando’s time, it wouldn’t fly. i’d like to see someone tell those guys they can’t walk into a girls locker room and tell a dirty joke.” the producer agreed with him as i protested. finally i realized i wasn’t going to change this guy’s mind and it wasn’t worth it for me to get into a fight with the talent. later, after this actor was very clearly on some sort of downer and kept falling asleep on and off set, he made a dirty joke about his penis while i was blotting his forehead between takes and then put his arm around my waist and said “we should dance!” i said no and finished my job and walked away. i am the only female on set today. later, 3 members of the crew came up to me (including the director, who i really like) and said it was probably more uncomfortable for them to watch it happen than it was for me to have it happen. no one said anything in the moment. no one stepped in. what we need is for our men to step in during those moments. when you don’t say something when you see something happening that is clearly wrong, you are perpetuating the problem...even if you are a well intentioned person. those of us with privilege should use that privilege to protect and respect those without it. teach others that this behavior is not ok. and stop hiring people like this when you see that their behavior is inappropriate. #metoo #timesup #onset #makeupartist #losangeles #hollywood #makeup #setlife

text:
#fbf | 1958. a house on the ocean on the east coast. marilyn opens norma’s eyes to the playwright’s betrayal: he’s been using their marriage, their love (her pureness) for a new script. he had always been impressed by her sensitivity and sense of reality; she responded to his gentleness. he spoke to her of the theater and suggested that she could make it. she committed and trained: for the theater, and for building a family with him. 
as norma reads the lines the playwright has written, she starts crying and choking on each paged she tries to swallow. marilyn stops her, and gladys appears carrying a container with boiling water making a circle around the two, singing softly: you ain’t been blue, no no no, you ain’t been blue till you got that moon indigo.

marilyn rejoices at the prospect of moving back to the west coast: another ill-fated marriage has failed, and she prepares a bottle of champagne to toast. norma attacks and kicks her in the stomach. they both touch their stomachs with their hands and realize they’re loosing blood. they had always wanted motherhood, and they were about to lose another chance to it.
_______________

text:
ever thought about altering your body? most of us have. at one time or another. make this a little bit bigger. that a little bit smaller. a nip here. a tuck there. smooth this. plump that. a constant race against mother nature and father time. molding to standards society has set. visual perfection. the key to our happiness. 
and then one day. it happened. insecurities on high. i met with plastic man. soon. everything would be okay. because we are, after all, just our bodies. right? the knife cut deep. silicone sisters weighing heavy on my chest. stitches and bandages. it was done.

laying there that night. alone. drugged. while mr. dj played his gig. i’m sure he couldn't feel his face. only to be woken up. later. when the gig was done. my new body. limp and incapacitated. was too much for the sadist to resist. terror rushed in. i was paralyzed. trapped in my own skin. could not move. could not speak. could not feel. i could only see. alive in a nightmare. i could not protect myself. how could this be happening? why was this happening? capsular contracture. a result of his rapture. 
denial set in. for several months. followed by the haunting. of constant flashbacks. then confusion. and anger. and sadness. and shame. then hearing from the assailant. threats. if i spoke of it. or was seen. in his turf. and that i was in fact. just insane. and it didn’t happen that way. 
but it did.

i learned. to my surprise. it really can happen to anyone. it took 3 years. to bring this to light. i am not ashamed. i did nothing wrong. i did not want it. i did not ask for it. i did not deserve it. it was not my fault. i don’t want pity. just to be heard. 
i also learned. that i am not. just a body. or an object. i am a woman. with a voice. and a heart. and and soul. who deserves nothing less than. love. honesty. truth. and respect. 
me too.

#healing 
#mindbodyspiritemotions 
#release 
#speakup 
#metoo

text:
this went under the radar but according to bbc news beyonce has ended a business venture with topshop boss sir philip green by buying him out of ivy park, the gymwear label they founded together.

the pair launched ivy park two years ago, playing on the personal brand of the us singer and outspoken feminist.

the buyout comes weeks after sir philip was named as having taken legal action to prevent publication of allegations of sexual harassment of staff.

sir philip says he "categorically and wholly" denies the allegations.

however, beyoncé had faced pressure from campaigners to cut ties.

in a statement on thursday, ivy park said: "after discussions of almost a year, parkwood has acquired 100% of the ivy park brand. topshop - arcadia will fulfil the existing orders."

text: in 2006, civil rights activist tarana burke sat in her room, took out a piece of paper, wrote “me too” across the top, and created an action plan for a movement that supported all survivors of sexual violence. now, #metoo has become a global movement, and while its mission is often misinterpreted, tarana is determined to keep working to dismantle the building blocks of sexual violence: power and privilege. “power and privilege doesn't always have to destroy and take -- it can be used to serve and build,” she says. to watch her ted talk from #tedwomen, visit go.ted.com/taranaburke

text:
this is not consent 🙌🏼
this is my own solidarity with the 17 yr old rape victim in the recent court case. our cruel justice system needs to stop re-traumatizing victims and survivors of sexual assault and rape. it is completely unacceptable and is a direct factor of the many rape incidents that remain unreported. 
living my best life ❤️✨
also, sharing this helps me personally to feel free and empowered. i am free from feeling fear, guilt and shame of my own sexual desire as a woman. for the first time in my life, i’m owning my desire/ living my best life😊 #thisisnotconsent #ibelieveher #stopvictimblaming  #metoo #notaskingforit #endrapeculture #goals #xmaslingerie  #livingmybestlife ✨

text:
il quinto incontro: nel quinto incontro di donne (non più anonime – confronto sul femminicidio, abbiamo ospitato teresa margolles, in collaborazione con: real academia de españa en roma, associazione culturale dello scompiglio, angel moya garcia, francesco martone. l’artista, che parla in pubblico per la seconda volta nella sua vita, esamina attraverso la sua modalità artistica le cause e le conseguenze sociali delle uccisioni, della violenza di genere, della povertà e dell’ordine sociale ed economico che rendono “normali” certe morti violente, vittime della povertà e della guerra tra narcotrafficanti in messico. tra le artiste che maggiormente hanno trattato il tema, le sue opere di crudo realismo, esprimono una ferma condanna e mostrano gli effetti sulle famiglie delle vittime, nelle comunità e nello spazio urbano. lo spettatore in prima persona, partecipa al dolore e alla sofferenza familiare e collettiva derivanti dalla brutalità del crimine organizzato, traslitterando da una dimensione individuale a una dimensione collettiva e universale.
la riproduzione e la diffusione del video che abbiamo prodotto sono assolutamente vietate a tutela della sicurezza dell’artista, perciò vi possiamo proporre solo delle immagini (ph. credits & courtesy: albumarte). roma, 5 giugno 2017
.
.

text:
a friend’s post today is a reminder of staying to true our authentic self, being vulnerable with our circle, being real no matter what. 
i am me through & through whether i am on social media or sitting in my living room....
with or without makeup..... dressed in sweats or a dress....
hair long or short, colored or natural....
size 4 or a size 14......
having a drink or on an alcohol hiatus.....
cussing like a sailor or sitting in a pew.....
being “happily” married or wanting to strangle him.....
working out at the gym (pool) or eating a maple bacon donut.... flipping my shit with my kids or giving them my last ounce of strength..... wanting to be a great role model to lil man or crying that i will never measure up....
from being the “best” friend ever to wanting to lock myself away from everyone... i am me just as you are you....i am the same crazy, loudmouth, opinionated woman that you love or love to hate. 
managing public optics can be exhausting so stop. just be you....the world is adapt. ❤️
#mebeingvulnerable ❤️
.
.
.
.

text:
wolf of wall street (2013) ✨ margot robbie has spoken out about this famous scene with leonardo dicarprio saying - ‘filming the scene was 'weird' and 'embarrassing' in reality, as she was in a tiny room with 30 crew members, all male, watching her. she explained: 'it doesn't come across when you're watching the movie, but in reality we're in a tiny bedroom with 30 crew crammed in. all men. for 17 hours i'm pretending to be touching myself. it's just a very weird thing and you have to bury the embarrassment and the absurdity, really deep, and fully commit.' that scene in particular had actually been the very scene margot had to audition with to bag her part in the movie. previously speaking about the awkward audition, margot revealed how she went off-script and slapped her co-star dicaprio across the face instead of kissing him in the hope of impressing movie bosses. 
she revealed how she was fully prepped for the scene after rehearsing it with her 'poor, poor' manager dylan in an interview with vogue. margot revealed: 'i was in his office for hours asking to do the take again, while he was probably thinking, "dear god, this is so uncomfortable."' 🥀 follow @cinemarea for more ✨

text_retweet:
a recent report claims that google employees internally discussed burying search results for conservative media outlets like breitbart news and the daily caller. one google engineer made his intentions clear by commenting, “let’s make sure that we reverse things in four years.”
a recent report from the daily caller claims that employees at tech giant google discussed burying conservative media, including breitbart and the daily caller, within the company’s search results. the article claims that employees referred to both news outlets as “opinion blogs” and discussed de-ranking the websites within google’s search results in an attempt to “make sure that we reverse things in four years.”
the daily caller alleges that according to leaked internal emails, google employees expressed their dismay at hillary clinton’s loss in the 2016 presidential elections and discussed ways to prevent president trump winning a second term. google engineer scott byer wrote in an email correspondence dated nov. 9, 2016: “this was an election of false equivalencies, and google, sadly, had a hand in it.” byers further referred to both breitbart news and the daily caller stating: “how many times did you see the election now card with items from opinion blogs (breitbart, daily caller) elevated next to legitimate news organizations? that’s something that can and should be fixed.”
some of byers colleagues reportedly expressed issues with manipulating search results so blatantly and offered alternative solutions, one engineer named uri dekel admitted that he was a clinton supporter but still did not agree with manually altering search results.
“thinking that breitbart, drudge, etc. are not ‘legitimate news sources’ is contrary to the beliefs of a major portion of our user base is partially what got us to this mess."
⠀⠀⠀
#repost @wearebreitbart

text:
¿recién ahora hablás? .
.
**** .
.
"me parece desubicado que vengas con esta cuestión ahora; si no hablaste en su momento, lo lamento, ya es tarde". .

a lo largo de mi vida escuché este tipo de sentencias en varias oportunidades. me las han dicho con tono determinante y convencido. con ese timbre de voz justo; ese que te deja así de chiquitito y fuera de juego. y, al escucharlas, algo en mí flaqueaba y yo proseguía como si lo afirmado fuera verdad: no, no tengo derecho a reflotar temas ásperos del pasado; debería haber hablado antes. .

una de las primeras veces que me dijeron algo semejante fue durante mi primer noviazgo. no me acuerdo qué había pasado, pero sí recuerdo que estuve mucho tiempo bastante mal. hasta que un día hablé, tímida, pero me animé y hablé y la respuesta fue: "típico de las mujeres salir con un reproche mil años después, ¿por qué no lo hablaste en el momento?" y yo, claro, quedé descalificada. quedé muda. tan muda, que por muchos años creí que si no tenía valor de expresarme en el instante en el cual se suceden los hechos, entonces era mejor callarme para siempre. .

pero la experiencia, sanar mi alma, escucharme y aprender a escuchar, me demostraron lo contrario: nunca es tarde para hablar. 
entonces, ante la pregunta de por qué no lo hablé en el momento, hoy ya no me paralizo ni quedo desdibujada. .

a veces no hablo porque en ese instante no sabría siquiera qué decir. no hablo porque mis emociones, mi ser y todo lo que me compone, no siempre son capaces de asimilar ni analizar las situaciones en ese presente. a veces, ni distingo de manera consciente que algo en ese encuentro me afectó en lo profundo; no lo sé hasta que un día me despierto y, como con el clic del enamoramiento, de pronto la realidad se me revela, logro identificarla y, entonces, comprendo. 
y a veces es por miedo; otras, porque sentimos vergüenza. a mí me costó muchísimo pronunciar en voz alta los desengaños que había vivido con mi ex pareja. "¿cómo.. (sigue). .

a lo largo de mi vida escuché este tipo de sentencias en varias oportunidades. me las han dicho con tono determite y convencido. con ese timbre de voz justo; ese que te deja así de chiquitito y fuera de juego. y, al escucharlas, algo en mí flaqueaba y yo proseguía como si lo afirmado fuera verdad: no, no tengo derecho a reflotar temas ásperos del pasado; debería haber hablado antes. .

una de las primeras veces que me dijeron algo semejante fue durante mi primer noviazgo. no me acuerdo qué había pasado, pero sí recuerdo que estuve mucho tiempo bastante mal. hasta que un día hablé, tímida, pero me animé y hablé y la respuesta fue: "típico de las mujeres salir con un reproche mil años después, ¿por qué no lo hablaste en el momento?" y yo, claro, quedé descalificada. quedé muda. tan muda, que por muchos años creí que si no tenía valor de expresarme en el instante en el cual se suceden los hechos, entonces era mejor callarme para siempre. .

pero la experiencia, sanar mi alma, escucharme y aprender a escuchar, me demostraron lo contrario: nunca es tarde para hablar. 
entonces, ante la pregunta de por qué no lo hablé en el momento, hoy ya no me paralizo ni quedo desdibujada. .

a veces no hablo porque en ese instante no sabría siquiera qué decir. no hablo porque mis emociones, mi ser y todo lo que me compone, no siempre son capaces de asimilar ni analizar las situaciones en ese presente. a veces, ni distingo de manera consciente que algo en ese encuentro me afectó en lo profundo; no lo sé hasta que un día me despierto y, como con el clic del enamoramiento, de pronto la realidad se me revela, logro identificarla y, entonces, comprendo. 
y a veces es por miedo; otras, porque sentimos vergüenza. a mí me costó muchísimo pronunciar en voz alta los desengaños que había vivido con mi ex pareja. "¿cómo.. (sigue). .

text:
“my name is autumn and i was sexually abused by my stepdad from the time i was 9 years old until i was 16. it started when one night he climbed into my top bunk and laid beside me. he fondled my breasts and then put his hand down my pj bottoms and touched and rubbed me. he told me that he loved me more than a daughter and not to tell anyone what happened because “no one would understand”. over the years he would ask me if i liked it when he touched me and i would say no. i would tell him to stop but he would ignore me or if he did stop he would get mad at me. one day in february when i was out with my mom, aunt and her baby i finally told my mom. i am lucky that my mom never questioned if i was telling the truth and as soon as we got home she kicked my stepdad. charges were pressed but justice would not come because it was found his right to a swift trial was violated. his charges were stayed. i still deal with guilt to this day over it. but i am strong.

i will not let him hold power over me. i am now in the social work field and help women and children fleeing abuse by working in a transition home with the elizabeth fry society. i plan on finishing my degree and figuring out where i want to go from there. i am a survivor and i am strong.” - @autumnostrom 
#november #autumnarmy #rosearmy #nomeansno #metoo #together #womenempowerment #socialworker #socialworkersareheroes

text:
warning: post may contain triggering information. ⠀
⠀
today's fact, as part of our ongoing support of the @unwomen #orangetheworld #hearmetoo global movement to eliminate violence against women & girls, is about the #sexualharassment ⠀
⠀
"sexual harassment includes unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favours, and other verbal or physical harassment of a sexual nature"⠀
⠀
we are in a society growing ever more aware of the prevalence of #sexualharassment in all its forms, and although there is greater awareness of the problem, women and girls the world over are still subjected to it. ⠀
⠀
some activists state that men should ask the women in their lives about their experiences with #sexualharassment and they will quickly realise how common it actually is.⠀
⠀
the #metoo movement has given millions of women voices to call out their abusers and to share their experiences. ⠀
⠀
a common thread in these stories is the fear that women experience from day to day, carrying out the most mundane of tasks.⠀
⠀
sexual harassment is a spectrum, and in order to combat it women & girls need to continue calling it our when they see it and when it happens to them, but, to truly eliminate it we need to educate men. men need to know the spectrum, to know what is appropriate conduct and what isn't. men are needed to call out other men on sexual harassment and to publicly show they do not condone these actions, regardless of where they fall on the spectrum.

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like ‘drain the swamp’ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the ‘deep state’ that weren’t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman
the independent

text:
abused & alone: prison rape in the #metoo era

by news beatnovember 29, 2018

listen to the episode “abused & alone: prison rape in the #metoo era with #closerosies co-creator #kathymorse.  click on 
https://www.usnewsbeat.com/2018/11/29/prison-rape-me-too/#story
 for more information about this important issue

the united states has reached a pivotal moment in its history, when women are increasingly speaking out about sexual assault. yet there’s one institution where sexual violence is pervasive but receives little recognition from the outside world: prisons. according to government statistics, the number of reported sexual assaults in these facilities tripled between 2011 and 2014—a sign that either more people are speaking out and/or government agencies are taking the issue more seriously. however, only a small percentage of these attacks are corroborated. the perpetrators of sexual abuse are both inmates and staff—with the latter representing the very people sworn to protect inmates. at this crucial moment, incarcerated survivors are trying to speak out with the hope that the #metoo movement will help bring these oft-forgotten horror stories to the fore.

#timesupcloserosies🌹
 #closerosies
#metoobehindbars @nycmayorsoffice @nygovcuomo
name: CLOSE ROSIES

text:
mae carol jemison (born october 17, 1956) is an american engineer, physician and nasa astronaut.
she became the first african american woman to travel in space when she went into orbit aboard the space shuttle endeavour on september 12, 1992.
after medical school and a brief general practice, jemison served in the peace corps from 1985 until 1987, when she was selected by nasa to join the astronaut corps.
she resigned from nasa in 1993 to found a company researching the application of technology to daily life.
she has appeared on television several times, including as an actress in an episode of star trek: the next generation.
she is a dancer and holds nine honorary doctorates in science, engineering, letters, and the humanities.
she is the current principal of the 100 year starship organization. 
jemison's first book, find where the wind goes (2001), is a memoir of her life written for children.
she describes her childhood, her time at stanford, in the peace corps and as an astronaut.
book report found that the "explanation of her encounters with biased professors and their treatment of her on the basis of stereotypes, rather than intelligence, are presented very realistically."

text:
rp @hudsontarlow a big reason for me not getting heavily involved with vegan activism after initially going vegan was due to my fear of being judged at school.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
in fact, i didn’t use my last name for the first few months of my social media activism because i was worried of receiving criticism if people found my account.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
but as time has continued, i’ve found that one of the best way to combat this fear of judgement is by putting ourselves in the position of the animals, and thinking from their perspective.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
for me, once i truly started thinking about the hardships and abuse that farmed animals endure, and compared it to the hardships i was afraid of going through at school from stepping out of my comfort zone, the fears i once faced became nothing compared to the suffering of the animals.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
pakistani women grow up experiencing sexual harassment on a daily basis. we are groped while walking through crowded markets. cheap songs are sung at us. men give us cringeworthy expressions with sexual connotations. in buses, movie theatres, concerts and universities, we are pinched, our breasts are touched. sometimes it happens at the hands of a teacher, sometimes at the hands of a security guard, who smiles at us after violating our privacy. sometimes, when we visit the doctor for a breast scan, we know he made us undress more than what was needed for the procedure.
.
we are a country full of zainabs and of sexual predators. sometimes it’s a male cousin who tries to make a pass at us when we are found alone and unprotected. sometimes, a brother- in- law walks into our room and lies down on the bed next to us, as we stay up late to prepare for an exam. sometimes, we are raped every night by a father who promised to protect us when he adopted us as infants. sometimes, we are molested at the hands of our biological father. that’s sickening and shocking but it is true. sometimes we tell our mother but she doesn’t believe us. sometimes, she believes us but has nowhere to take us. sometimes, it’s the male servant who robbed us of our innocence while playing a ‘game’ with us. sometimes it is the uncle our parents trust. and sometimes, it’s the rickshaw-wala who keeps staring back at us from the rearview mirror while we struggle to keep our dupatta where it should be, despite the wind. we suffer from sexual harassment at the hands of our male colleagues too. explicit jokes about the female body are cracked in our presence. but we stay silent as we don’t know how to prove what he did to us. we need the job and the money too.
. 
we suffer from sexual harassment of all forms every single day, at workplaces, on the streets, at educational institutes, at hospitals and at our homes too. we are traumatized. we want an end to sexual harassment so that we can live the complete lives we deserve.
. 
thank you @unwomenpakistan for the opportunity to contribute to the 16 day #hearmetoo campaign against sexual harassment of women. #orangetheworld #truestories @unwomen

text:
press release: announcing duchess international magazine print copy launch!

for immediate release
november 22, 2018

yes! we’ve got great news and we’re super excited to share!

duchess international magazine is proud to announce the launch of her maiden print edition –‘the magnificent woman’, on sunday, 9th december 2018 at the grand ibis hotel, ikeja, lagos.

the initiative, driven by the need to improve the reading experience of our esteemed readers will provide well grounded information on lifestyle, health and wellness and fashion. 
we’ve got an interesting lineup of events: enlightening discussions, networking opportunities and high profile personalities in attendance.

outstanding individuals who have done well in their chosen fields will be honoured as well.

notable speakers and guest at the event include; dr. elishama ideh, ms. yemisi jenkins mbe, ms. bisola munis and a host of others.

let’s root for each other and watch one another grow. magnificent women we all are!

don’t be left out. save the date!

text: . thank you to friends and acquaintances, virtual and rl (even strangers around the world have been supportive ❤). . . i have had a very difficult few years, on several levels, and i am here, alive, because of the support and loving inclusiveness of those beautiful souls who acknowledge my existence, and have been encouraging of my work and my sensitive expressive spirit, (especially with this latest series #myvaginaisthewindowtoyoursoul : paintings, digital collage, sculptural construct) . . . thank you to those of you who walk your talk, and are genuinely supportive and inclusive . much love and respect . we need one another ❤ it is very scary to live through vulnerability, to put myself out there in my truth, dark and light in equal parts . . . thank you thank you thank you . i acknowledge you and your passions, your healing, and cheer you on as well . lovelovelove is the only way . . . #healingtogether #community #yyt #nlartist #metoo #metoomovement #ibelieveyou #timesup #silentnomore #womenempoweringwomen #humansempoweringhumans #solidarity #reclaimingmybody #reclaimingmypower #artofhealing

text:
#realtalkfriday is the glass half full or half empty?..
.
the optimist says the glass is half full. 
the pessimist says the glass is half empty. 
the cynic says the glass is twice as big as it needs to be. 
the realist says the glass contains half the required amount of liquid for it to overflow. 
but i say it’s not about whether the glass is half empty or half full, it’s whether there is something in the glass at all.

it has been quite a year and i've been all of those things above with regards to my own 'glass'. over this whole year i've run two marathons, bagged a marathon pb, ran two ultras, came first lady in one of them, pb'd a half marathon and walked away with a podium spot. but there's even more in the pipeline and there's some pretty exciting stuff coming up too #watchthisspace. 👀
.
but what i didn't tell you was that whilst i was doing all this, behind the scenes i was fighting my own battle. a personal and legal one, that has lasted the entire year. i had to give statements, i had to be video'd at a police house, i had to relay my account, my truth over and over. but when push came to shove, i was told it couldn't and wouldn't be taken any further. right then and there i was plummeted into the biggest choice i've probably ever had to make. on the one hand i can feel like i've lost, that i failed, and feel anger so strong it takes your breath away (which i did for a while!) or choose to pick my self up and believe in my heart that winning a legal battle is not the same as getting your life back. i chose the latter. and i win every single day because i choose to take my glass and fill it with whatever i want, however high up to the brim. .
.
and the same goes for those running metrics we all constantly chase after. its ok to want to beat that time from before, or rank a little (or alot) higher. its ok to want to win and its perfectly ok if you don't. your dreams are going to be different from his and hers because they are created by you. but just remember you always have a choice with what you choose to fill your glass with. pb's and podium spots are wonderful things, but if you feel you're not enough without it, you'll never feel enough with it. ❤️

text:
as some of you know for the past few years virtue + vice has been working closely with @womenweave in maheshwar.

womenweave helps to provide safe and dignified fabric weaving work for women who have been abused or lost their husbands or need financial aid. (this year we were featured in @forbes, yay!) every month about 15 women approach womenweave asking for jobs. sadly, machines are limited and there have not been any openings.

but this is where you can help!

yarn spinning wheels cost 17000rs, that's about $250. for every spinning wheel virtue + vice is able to purchase we are able to create 1 job for a woman in desperate need. our goal is to purchase 2 wheels to employ 2 women this holiday season.

any little bit helps! link to donate if the bio...

text:
a few days ago, when i was approached by @unwomenpakistan to collaborate and participate in their campaign for ending violence against women and sexual harassment, i felt proud. that is because for me, my goals for blogging are clear. while i do love having fun with it, talk about lipsticks, fashion, cracking lame jokes and sharing my love for nature, the posts that satisfy me the most are those in which i speak about the society. i try to use my platform to talk about the changes i would like to see in our society on an individual and a holistic level. these are the posts that get me into trouble as well. i get mean comments, people raise fingers and aunties come crashing down on me. but the contentment that somewhere i made sense to someone or was able to help out or change perspectives is far greater than the boos.🌻
.
anyway, the point here was that when you put yourself out there for people to see, you don't know who's watching. in the midst of many who always find something to pull you down with, there are some who silently support you. and one day, bring forth an opportunity that brings you pride as well as the satisfaction that people can see what you're trying to do with your platform. it was an absolute pleasure to associate with @unwomenpakistan and make a very small contribution to keep the momentum of the #metoo campaign going with #hearmetoo.
.
for those who are unaware of the campaign, i'd like to shed some light on it. the #hearmetoo campaign aims to encourage women to speak up and talk about their personal experiences of sexual harassment. i understand that it is easier said than done, but we have to be strong for those who are not being able to be strong. the more we speak, the more we contribute towards creating an environment where women are supported and believed, where they can live freely, with dignity and safety.  we need to keep the momentum going so sexual harassment and its consequences are a part of the dialogue. sexual harassment is a criminal offence. hence, we need to create an environment where speaking up about it doesn't bring us shame. it brings us justice. #orangetheworld
. 
read my write up in the previous post. 🌹

text:
"including 'other' voices outside of the dominant (white, male) voice help to contextualize & complete discourses in the media." - leslie stevens, @mccnyu grad student and weber shandwick scholar.
.
leslie has dedicated her work to examining diversity and inclusion in the media, including the role of black twitter in our culture and the silencing of black women in the #metoo movement. when asked about the importance of incorporating "other" voices in the media landscape, she said, "i think it’s really important to be critical about how cultural institutions are constructed and maintained. this is what we have been exploring so far in the program. many of the pillars of society that we assume are a given are really constructed by specific systems that allow one entity to dominate. the media, for example, is perceived as a societal pillar that is composed of many public opinions, interests, and experiences, when in reality, it often privileges white, male voices. in being critical, we should seek to expose how certain stories are silenced, amplified, passed over, or repeated. in shedding light, we find ways to get better at representing all the stories that come together to create our culture. i think black voices are those that often get silenced, but there are brown voices too, non-gender binary voices, women’s voices, voices of those who are disabled, and intersections of all of these. including “other” voices outside of the dominant (white, male) voice help to contextualize and complete discourses in the media. in the end, we all want to have our stories told and represented in media; from news to entertainment to sports and politics, we want to see ourselves reflected in whatever kind of media we’re consuming."
.
read the full q&a and learn about our media diversity scholarship in our link in bio.
.
.
.
.
[image description: leslie standing in front of nyu steinhardt building]
.
.
.
.

survivors need a safe friendly haven where help is available by trusted professionals. the warif centre offers free medical treatment, counselling and social welfare services to all clients. starting the journey to full recovery.

and here is the original photo 💜 a curacao sunset 🌅 do you see what i did to abstract yesterday’s image? i zoomed in a little just above the row of clouds, swirled it in the rollworld app and then flipped it around.. just saying: anything is possible! which image do you like most? (in case you missed my previous post please check it out to understand the story 😉) happy weekend everyone! 🥰
...
ps. this sunday i’m planning to visit the house/village where i was abused as a child. my loving partner marco is joining me on this journey ❤️ going back there to finish off what once started there makes a lot of sense to me, and i’m ready 🙏 i’ll let you know how it works out 😘

text:
มันปลื้มใจนะ ที่มีคนมาบอกว่า 💕"โชคดีที่ได้เจอ โชคดีที่ได้รู้จัก " 💕
เป็นคนให้เต็มร้อย(💯)และไม่เคยน้อยลง (นอกจากเหตุผลหรือสิ่งที่เขาทำมันทำให้%ลดลงเอง )  จากทุกสิ่งทุกความรู้สึกและ ความจริงใจ ความช่วยเหลือที่เราให้ สิ่งที่ได้กลับมาก็คือความรู้สึกดีๆที่ผู้รับ  #สัมผัสได้ด้วยหัวใจ #touch ❤ แต่ถ้าใครที่เขาไม่เห็นถึงความรู้สึกนั้น เขาก็ไม่สมควรที่จะได้รับความรู้สึกนั้นตลอดไป  #ให้กับคนที่คู่ควรและเห็นคุณค่า #deserve  #grateful #metoo
hashtags: #สัมผัสได้ด้วยหัวใจ, #Touch, #ให้กับคนที่คู่ควรและเห็นคุณค่า, #deserve, #Grateful, #Metoo

text:
he does not leave any signs of his walk down this lane. he takes this passage daily. people are shouting comments. but it's all in slow motion, like movies. as he passes, he faces all kinds of looks. the presence of haters all around. he holds on to the ground, yet another walk it is. isn't this path what you call stress? isn't this path what you call self consciousness? isn't this path what is actually a competition against all beauties & style statements ? he's us. he's us all. we all take a walk down that lane every day, every minute, every single second. you ignore,but you know deep down you don't. you are hurt by your very own existence, how you truly are.you look in the mirror -not through your eyes, but from the other's. 
yes, you do not leave any signs of the walk down this lane.

the #metoo movement has triggered a painful memory for actor tish, who says she received unwanted sexual attention from a hollywood insider almost a decade ago. when she rejected his advances, she says he grew angry and told her she'd never make it in hollywood. 
tish has not allowed his words to determine her future, but rather, she has used this as power to prove him wrong. she is now successful actor in hollywood making it just fine regardless of what her abuser had to say. 
tish, your determination is inspiring.
we are all behind you.

text:
this year has taught me the importance of privacy, self love and courage. the past 2 years have been the hardest years for me and yet here i stand, with a smile bigger than ever. you cannot control everything that happens to you, but you can damn well control how it will effects you and i chose to fight, hard.
i survived. i bettered myself. my smile continues to grow each day. and today i got the best news that only pushes me to work harder to get to where i want to be in life. so you didn’t break me, in fact, i should thank you for allowing me to hit my rock bottom, so that i could start anew.
here is to the start of a journey full of courage, self love, and positivity, with those who truly wish to share it with me! and a big ‘fuck you’ to you, because look at this smile.. you didn’t break me. so excuse me whilst i begin living my best life, with the best people. 
here is to me and my journey... it’s only the beginning 🥂 xoxo. -
-
-

text:
this one hit me pretty hard. we all have a different past and childhood. mine was something i don’t really love to look back on. dealing with an absent father, sexual abuse, domestic violence, drug use, becoming an adolescent and hanging out with the wrong kids. i was in really dark places and did things i wish i could erase. but i can’t. im not a victim of my past and don’t use it as an excuse anymore for my faults. i’m learning to heal those memories so i can become a better person instead of letting the violations the shame, the guilt, the anxiety hang over my head, keeping me from feeling like a beautiful confident women. we all are. we are not our past, it just shapes us into who we are. .
.
.

this one hit me pretty hard. we all have a different past and childhood. mine was something i don’t really love to look back on. dealing with an absent father, sexual abuse, domestic violence, drug use, becoming an adolescent and hanging out with the wrong kids. i was in really dark places and did things i wish i could erase. but i can’t. im not a victim of my past and don’t use it as an excuse anymore for my faults. i’m learning to heal those memories so i can become a better person instead of letting the violations the shame, the guilt, the anxiety hang over my head, keeping me from feeling like a beautiful confident women. we all are. we are not our past, it just shapes us into who we are. .
.
.

text:
putney by, sofka zinovieff 🍓
"she knew transformations were part of many stories." 🍓
putney is told through 3 points of view daphne, ralph, and jane. daphne had a sexual relationship when she was 13 with ralph who was in his 30's at the time! {the story is told through flashbacks from the past to the present.} 🍓
when daphne is in her 40's she realized that ralph had taken advantage of her when she was only 13. with the help of her {?friend?} jane, she tries to get a confession out of ralph for what he did years ago. 🍓
for a book that was difficult for me to read and get through i had a hard time putting it down. 🍓
putney dives deep into the discussions surrounding consent and abuse of power.  this book could be considered controversial/empowering to the #metoo movement. 🍓 ⭐⭐⭐⭐/5
i read this in a buddy read with @florenceandthebookparty and @gitana.eleni and many other wonderful bookstagramers🤗 i have loved our chats!!! this was such a fun book club group!!! can't wait to hear everyone's final thoughts on putney.

text:
in the light of the survey results released earlier this november about what young adults consider to be consent. 17% of men thinks a relationship is consent (9% women). 17% of men consider going home to someone late at night is consent(7% women). 33% of men think that laying naked with someone is consent (16% women). in the eyes of the new sexual consent law this is not consent, as it should be. consent can be given and then revoked, and it’s still valid. consent is given over and over again, until it is not. doesn’t matter if you’re going home for a one night stand or if you’re in a long term relationship. 90% of women were positive in relation to the new law, with the corresponding number of 62% for men. consent is not the circumstances, it’s the moment!
.
.
.
#samtyckeslagen #metoo #consentissexy #politicalcartoons

text:
coming up next at nightwood - grace by jane doe, january 8-26, 2019 @crowstheatre .

exquisitely told in a stunning blend of documentary theatre, striking visual projections and choreography, grace is a searing piece that ignites a pertinent discussion on the failures and limitations of the legal system. a true story about survival, hope, and the pursuit of justice at a time when provability still usurps truth in our courtrooms.

a nightwood theatre production in association with crow’s theatre | written by jane doe* | directed by andrea donaldson 
featuring michaela washburn, rose napoli, brenda robins and conrad coates .

tickets available at crowstheatre.com.

photography by @tanjatiziana .
#theato #toronto #grace #janedoe #torontotheatre #nightwood #theatrebywomen #feminist #legalsystem #metoo #documentarytheatre . . . *faced with the conflict between sharing her family’s story and protecting their privacy, the playwright has chosen the pseudonym of jane doe

text: between 25 november (the international day for the elimination of violence against women 2018) and 10 december (human rights day), the south african government (amongst others) marks sixteen days of activism for no violence against women and children. many of the most insidious forms of violence in south africa occur between intimate partners and in the home. dramatic need works with many vulnerable women and children using arts-based advocacy and community theatre to build awareness, self-confidence and help them to speak out against abuse and abusers. we also work with boys and young men to encourage them to better communicate and to express their anger and frustrations in a non-violent way. this form of psycosocial care is crucial if intimate partner violence is to be obliterated in future generations.  to mark these 16 days of advocacy for no violence against women and children we will be posting short videos of women from all walks of life, from all round the world, highlighting the appalling statistics in south africa of violence against women and children. please share these videos with people you love. it’s time for awareness and it’s time for change. . #thisneedstochange #countmein #heremetoo #creativechange #womenspeakfacts #metoo#gbvmuststop #16days  we acknowledge that gender-based violence exists in all communities, amongst all genders and affects both trans and cis-gendered people. we have specifically focused on women – and those who identify as women – and children during this campaign. dramatic need works in south africa and so this is where we have chosen to focus our advocacy. however, gender based violence of any form is abhorrent &we stand in solidarity with those who have experienced it, whatever their gender, wherever they are in the world.  in these videos we have done our best to use reliable and verifiable statistics. where statistics were not measured within the last two years we have indicated this. sexual violence &rape statistics are difficult to accurately measure due to low levels of reporting and the intimacy of the crime. for more information about the sources of these statistics see our blog! thank you kirsten @myfriendned

text:
i do not choose to be a common person. it is my right to be uncommon …
i seek opportunity … not security.
i want to take the calculated risk,
to dream and to build. to fail and to succeed....
i prefer the challenges of life to the guaranteed existence;
the thrill of fulfillment to the stale calm of utopia.
i will not trade freedom for beneficence
nor my dignity for a handout
i will never cower before any master
nor bend to any threat.
it is my heritage to stand erect, proud and unafraid;
to think and act for myself,
to enjoy the benefit of my creations. —————————————————
نمی‌خوام یه آدم معمولی باشم... این حقمه انتخاب کنم چی می‌خوام باشم... من دنبال موقعیت‌هام، نه امنیت. ریسک‌های برنامه‌ریزی شده رو دوست دارم، ساختن ‌و خراب‌کردن رو، باختن و برنده شدن رو... چالش‌های زندگی رو‌ به آرامش‌ ابدی ترجیح می‌دم؛ هیجان تلاش برای رسیدن به هدف، بارها شیرین‌تره از سکوت ساکن یوتوپیا... آزادی‌ام رو با هیچ وعده وعیدی عوض نمی‌کنم و ارزش‌هایم را به هیچ قیمتی نمی‌فروشم. جلوی هیچ اربابی دولا راست نمی‌شم و در برابر حرف زور کوتاه نمیام... این میراث منه که سر بلند بایستم‌، افکارم رو به زبان بیارم و از تاثیر زحماتم لذت ببرم. •

name: Sahar Zand سحر زند
tweet_full:
i do not choose to be a common person. it is my right to be uncommon …
i seek opportunity … not security.
i want to take the calculated risk,
to dream and to build. to fail and to succeed....
i prefer the challenges of life to the guaranteed existence;
the thrill of fulfillment to the stale calm of utopia.
i will not trade freedom for beneficence
nor my dignity for a handout
i will never cower before any master
nor bend to any threat.
it is my heritage to stand erect, proud and unafraid;
to think and act for myself,
to enjoy the benefit of my creations. —————————————————
نمی‌خوام یه آدم معمولی باشم... این حقمه انتخاب کنم چی می‌خوام باشم... من دنبال موقعیت‌هام، نه امنیت. ریسک‌های برنامه‌ریزی شده رو دوست دارم، ساختن ‌و خراب‌کردن رو، باختن و برنده شدن رو... چالش‌های زندگی رو‌ به آرامش‌ ابدی ترجیح می‌دم؛ هیجان تلاش برای رسیدن به هدف، بارها شیرین‌تره از سکوت ساکن یوتوپیا... آزادی‌ام رو با هیچ وعده وعیدی عوض نمی‌کنم و ارزش‌هایم را به هیچ قیمتی نمی‌فروشم. جلوی هیچ اربابی دولا راست نمی‌شم و در برابر حرف زور کوتاه نمیام... این میراث منه که سر بلند بایستم‌، افکارم رو به زبان بیارم و از تاثیر زحماتم لذت ببرم. •

text:
as a young girl, malala yousafzai defied the taliban terrorists in pakistan and demanded that girls be allowed to receive an education. she was shot in the head by a taliban gunman, but survived and went on to receive the nobel peace prize and is now an international champion of rights for the education of girls. 
she not only survived but triumphed in her journey and has gone on to become a fierce beacon of strength and hope for young women around the world who are fighting for the right to education. 
sanfe salutes the spirit of malala who inspires us to #standupforyourself

text:
the #metoo movement has propelled the world into discussing issues around sexual assault and abuse, but what happens when survivors come together and turn these shared negative experiences into a positive source of healing?  megan taylor, junior studio art, textiles major at #kentstate, is doing just that. when she is not creating art and music, she is on a mission to help survivors of sexual violence heal from their trauma.  inspired to name the group after a song she wrote, taylor founded the more than a body project (mtab) two years ago. with taylor serving as the president, the group has been steadily growing since, touching lives on kent state campus and beyond.  @morethanabodyproject 🌻

read more about megan's journey on our website. 
#ksuschoolofart #kentstate #morethanabody #🌻

👣

text_retweet:
💪🏻💕💪🏻
posted @withrepost • @marialiftstacoma when i was 21, i came to learn ways in which westernized yoga were problematic. you had people touching inappropriately and studios consciously segregating demographics that minorities like myself were in. if you weren’t wearing lululemon or making 50 grand a year, then you probably couldn’t make this movement part of your health. 
i got away from this oppressive feeling thanks to powerlifting. there were so many things that were revolutionary about this sport and still have benefits to someone’s transformation internally and externally. however being so involved with this sport and seeing how political this sport is, i came to the reality that my voice won’t matter at the top. i am not what this sport is making room for and perhaps it’s good to know my intersectional approach is best used elsewhere. i know i am not the only one who feels this way. 
even after writing letters of sexual harassment to the (all white) committee to investigate, even after asking why the transgender communities couldn’t get a fair response with their applications, even after asking for help from an organization that is “big on saying they’re here for their athletes”, i saw capitalism at its finest. there are so many dirty situations in these strength sports that i’ve heard about as the #metoo movement rises and it cements my decision to not give my money to organizations that don’t enforce a mission of safety, equality or inclusivity. 
i realized not only for my mental health but for my life, that i needed to step back from competing and simply come up to the surface of my life and just take a breath. i’ve been unlearning my “athlete” eating habits, i’ve had to retrain certain expectations in my workouts and am astonished with how much i’ve been able to experience liberation. i have done more recreational activities than i have in the last two years and i’m spending so much quality time with my friends and meeting new ones. i have taken my time (and money) to the outdoors where my convictions are honored, where i feel safe and where i don’t have to constantly fight to feel heard. (cont in comments)
name: Mary Medibles Consulting

text:
women journalists face sexual harassment in the newsroom and in the field. internews tanzania raises awareness of this issue with a psa launched during the '16 days of activism on gender based violence in the workplace' campaign. the psa, based on a real incident, shows a case of sexual harassment of a woman journalist while interviewing a source. the psa ends with the hotline number managed by tanzanian women lawyers association where people can report all cases of sexual harassment. 
usaid’s boresha habari implemented by internews in tanzania aims to support women journalists, and sextorsion is one of the biggest obstacle in their careers. 
#16daysofactivism #supportsurvivors #gbv #metoo

1. ”slutet” av mats strandberg. spännande bok om två unga människor de sista veckorna innan jorden går under.
2. ”draw the line” av amalia alvarez mfl. en serieantologi i spåren av #metoo
3. ”dagen då du förstörde allt” av linnéa dahlgren - tidigare elev på pg.

text:
i believe that true beauty shines from the inside out. the latest fashion and beauty products have nothing to do with it. it’s about loving yourself for who you are, not what you look like. it’s also about living a positive life and helping those who are in need. it’s about being the best human being you can possibly be. when i was about 16 years of age, i became interested in my natural beauty and myself. how important it is to be honest and truthful. of course almost every girl has had insecurities and maybe still does. true beauty is about being comfortable in your own skin not looking at a magazine that a women should look like. be who you want to be, not what people want to see. it isn't what's on the outside that counts; it's what's on the inside that matters. you're born to be real not perfect. one thing you can do better than others is be yourself. *

photography by: @moemaureen

text: full circle ⭕️ this is the title of the book i’ve been working on for a while now. no, i haven’t finished yet. the things i’m writing about are extremely painful so i’m having to take period mental breaks. for so long i was quiet about my story, ashamed , afraid of looking weak to others. i am finally telling my story. my mother had my when she was 16, she didn’t attend school past the 9th grade. my biological father had his parental right taken away for sexually abusing me. 70 percent of my childhood i spent under the influence of a meth addicted mother who abused me not only physically but mentally and living in other places that weren’t my home. i won’t lie ages 13-18 weren’t that bad. i was lucky to have an amazing man as my adopted father and a step mother who was a god send literally , i call her my living angel. my mother never recovered and is currently in prison. it’s hard , life is hard and we don’t always get to choose the cards handed to us. i joined the marine corps thinking it would save me but i quickly saw the dark parts of the military when i was raped within my first 6 months of service. throughout my military career i fell victim to different forms of sexual harassment and cyber bullying. was i perfect no , i’ve made a lot of mistakes and i’ve been a single mother since my son was 8 months old. i realize life is one big circle and the only person who can truly save me is the one in this picture. #military#metoo#survivor#veteran#poet#writer#author#model#photoshoot#atlanta#atl#atlmodel#dreamer#marinecorps#usmc#georgia#miami#hollywood#fitness

#pobunjenečitateljke na ovogodišnjem befem festivalu! 
2. xii 15:00‒16:00 „on me voli na svoj način“: dođite da zajedno razgovaramo o zastupljenosti rodno zasnovanog nasilja u 
književnosti i pop-kulturi. razgovor će se voditi interaktivno, odnosno uz ravnopravno učešće publike, 
tako što ćemo se podsetiti citata iz savremenih književnih dela i replika iz popularnih televizijskih serija i 
kontektuelizovati ih u odnosu na žensku svakodnevicu. u razgovoru će, između ostalog, biti reči o krat-
kim pričama regionalnih autorki rumene bužarovske i slađane nine perković, romanima elene ferante 
i sali runi, serijama sluškinjina priča i devojke, kao i o pokretu #metoo. cilj razgovora je da sve zajedno 
kritički sagledamo umetničku obradu tema rodno zasnovanog nasilja, kao i lično, političko i feminističko 
u kulturi, a s fokusom na savremene autorke.

text:
what now exists in the room that was once my childhood bedroom? 
a shrine for elephants, my little sister’s.

thinking about things left behind. 
yours and mine. 
thinking about excess. 
thinking about my family and kentucky and color pink power and privilege. 
thinking about all that hangs in bed over our head’s hearts beating holiday cheer and oh yeah—  me too now exists in the womb that was once my childhood bedroom.

#poem #myoldkentuckyhome #metoo #privilege #tackychristmaslights #holidaycheer #journal #nostalgia

text:
jag är trött och borde egentligen sova. istället ligger jag i min säng och skriver medans mina öron fylls av min ledsna lista på spotify, samtidigt som jag tänker. tänker på hur jag hamnade här och hur jag förändrats. jag har varit trött så länge och jag har ingen aning om vad jag är trött på eller vad jag känner längre.
-
inuti är det någonting som har brustit, det syns inte utanpå men jag känner i varje hjärtslag och varje andetag att jag är någon annan och inte kan stanna här. 
men alla säger till mig att fortsätta,
”du är stark, du klarar det här”
samtidigt som jag ligger i min säng med rinnande tårar på min kind och en kropp som skakar. jag känner mig inte stark längre.
-
för två år sedan förändrades jag.
två år sedan en kille tog i tillfällig akt att ge sig på mig och min kropp. han lyssnade aldrig när jag sa ifrån,
”nej jag vill inte, kan du sluta”
jag minns hans händer smekandes på min rygg. helt plötsligt hade hans händer tafsat på min rumpa och mina bröst. han försökte kyssa mig ett flertal gånger, både på mina läppar och min hals. det var obehagligt. han hade sina händer innanför min tröja och sa,
”jag såg”
kvällen innan frågade han vad jag har för färg på mina nippels. när tiden hade tickat sa han,
”jag släpper dig men bara på ett villkor, om du ger mig någonting bra tillbaka” 
jag visste inte vad jag skulle göra. jag frös till och stod där alldeles stilla, det hände så mycket.. men jag fick gå tillslut.
-
efter några månaders tid började verkligheten komma tillbaka, när man börjar känna skam. vad skulle familj, släkt, vänner och skolan tycka? förhöret med polisen, samtalen som ringdes hem, mötena med socialpedagogen.
jag mådde jättedåligt.
killen som utsatte mig för detta var en kompis. det värsta var aldrig att förlora han, utan att han tog med sig en bit av mig och stunden efter. rädslan och skräcken han gav mig är fortfarande kvar hos mig och det är jobbigt. men jag har bestämt mig för att försöka gå vidare och släppa allting nu. jag har insett att det inte finns någonting att göra åt det i nuläget. till alla ungdomar eller individer där ute, var försiktiga. det är en lång väg och ett helvete att ta sig ut ifrån. 
#metoo #ettnejärettnej

text:
|mental well-being|positive daily habits|

walking my barney bear this morning got me thinking about my own mental health and well-being and is my mental health as good as it could be🤔

i have suffered severe anxiety at times and i have learnt to recognise the triggers through years of trial and error. as part of my growth in this area i am a certified mental health first aider because i genuinely believe looking after our #mentalhealth is so important and raising awareness to support each other with #mentalwellbeing is equally as important, socially and in the workplace. as a life coach i want to serve my clients in the best way i can so this training was obvious for me. 
surviving severe traumas and challenges in life affects us in many ways but especially our mental well-being. looking forward to an amazing future can be difficult if your mind is not mentally strong. 
i do work hard on this area and have introduced a number of good habits to help me with this. 
walking with barney and enjoying being outside in nature is one of those habits i have introduced and i try to do most days. no one is perfect though, so find out what works for you and don’t compare, and if you don’t manage every day that’s ok, you are slowly making changes and that’s the important thing. 😊

what habits are you implementing every day to help with your mental well-being?  i’d love to know in the comments below. 👇🏻 #mentalhealth #mentalwellbeing #mindset #lifecoachforwomen #confidence #anxiety #control #metoo #trauma #survivor #onehabit #positivethinking #positivehabits
name: Life Coach

walking my barney bear this morning got me thinking about my own mental health and well-being and is my mental health as good as it could be🤔

i have suffered severe anxiety at times and i have learnt to recognise the triggers through years of trial and error. as part of my growth in this area i am a certified mental health first aider because i genuinely believe looking after our #mentalhealth is so important and raising awareness to support each other with #mentalwellbeing is equally as important, socially and in the workplace. as a life coach i want to serve my clients in the best way i can so this training was obvious for me. 
surviving severe traumas and challenges in life affects us in many ways but especially our mental well-being. looking forward to an amazing future can be difficult if your mind is not mentally strong. 
i do work hard on this area and have introduced a number of good habits to help me with this.

text:
i talked to my email community a few weeks ago people in our lives that aren’t hurtful, but they aren’t helpful either.
*
how many people in your circle would give you $10 for a meal but wouldn’t pay $10 to support a product or service you’re launching? supporting your business would help you buy your own meals, but they aren’t able to see that vision.
*
they are not harmful to your journey, but they may not be able to help you get to the next level either. you still love them and you always will, but they may not be able to go with you to that next level. try to accept it for what it is and keep pushing forward, even if it’s without them...❤️❤️

text:
⠀
движение #metoo, созданное поддержать жертв сексуального насилия, набирает обороты. теперь в свете этого движения арт-активисты призывают пересмотреть информацию, которую содержат пояснительные таблички к музейным экспонатам. например, чикагская художница мишель хартни создала проект «корректная история искусства», в рамках которого она размещает собственные таблички рядом с работами художников, которых она считает мизогинистами, абьюзерами и сексистами.
⠀
недавно мишель хартни провела акцию в музее метрополитен, разместив без разрешения сотрудников музея личное описание к картине поля гогена "две таитянки". на табличке написано:
⠀
«мы больше не будем поклоняться алтарю творческого гения, игнорируя цену, которую часто платят за этот гений. по правде говоря, мы давно уже усвоили бы этот урок, если бы не наше культурное восхищение творческими и могущественными людьми, которые в то же время являются "непредсказуемыми" или "переменчивыми" и поступают отвратительно».
⠀
в блэк-лист хартни входят и другие художники: пабло пикассо (называвший женщин "машинами для страданий"), бальтюс (создаваший сексуализированные изображения девочек-подростков), ну, и гоген (у которого были три девочки-невесты на таити).
name: Собака Босха

i become more like me, 
and less like them. ❤️

text:
d:chile:2018 “when i was a little girl, a man touched me without my consent. i was nine. at the time, i didn’t think about it as something bad. but the same guy touched two other girls, and they spoke up  about it. my grandmother grabbed me and told me, “you don’t have to let anybody touch you.” then something clicked and i understood what happened to me was wrong. i never wanted to say anything until now. so, i feel staying silent didn’t help me.”
•••••
for the 16 days of activism, footage will focus on “women ending conflict” by launching a campaign from our girl-talk-girl program featuring new stories from and produced by young women in the school of psychology at pontificia universidad católica de chile. each young woman is the first person in her family to attend university. gtg provides a safe platform for global young women to share experiences of gender-based violence and to heal. [girl-talk-girl was generously funded by the us embassy in santiago and by donors like you.].
.
.
.

text:
“gender equality is human fight, not a female fight” 
saya percaya, bahwa setiap manusia dalam satu kali hidupnya akan menemukan suatu cara untuk mengabdi dalam kemanusiaan, dan untuk saya inilah cara yang saya temukan.

selain menyibukkan jari jemari di dunia maya, saya ingin memberikan dukungan secara nyata, dukungan kepada korban atau penyintas, dukungan kepada mereka yang berjuang untuk ruang hidup, kehidupan, dan penghidupan.

kalau kalian tidak sibuk, datanglah mari ke 16 film festival, sisihkan waktu sore hari, kami akan bersuara lebih kencang melalui berbagai medium seni dan pertukaran narasi hingga 10 desember nanti.

jika sibuk membuat tidak bisa datang, boleh gantinya ikut berpartisipasi mendukung dengan mengampanyekan #hearmetoo melalui twibbon yang dapat diunduh di bit.ly/twibbon16ffbali18 dan jangan lupa sisipkan tagar #hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali

selain menyibukkan jari jemari di dunia maya, saya ingin memberikan dukungan secara nyata, dukungan kepada korban atau penyintas, dukungan kepada mereka yang berjuang untuk ruang hidup, kehidupan, dan penghidupan.

kalau kalian tidak sibuk, datanglah mari ke 16 film festival, sisihkan waktu sore hari, kami akan bersuara lebih kencang melalui berbagai medium seni dan peukaran narasi hingga 10 desember ti.

text:
dr ford is a psychology professor based at palo alto university and hold a phd in educational psychology and research design. in early 2018, dr ford approached the washington post and her congress member, anna eshoo, in confidence; reporting that she had been sexually assaulted by supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh when they attended high school together in 1982. dr ford said she felt a civil duty to report her experience of the conduct of mr kavanaugh, who would likely occupy the highest judicial office in the united states. 
details of the report and her identity were publicly revealed in september 2018. from this time, dr ford became the subject of harassment, intimidation, disbelief, and even death threats. her credibility was attacked within public and political spheres, with many questioning why she had waited decades to make the allegations public, and whether she stood to gain personally by making these allegations. dr ford and mr kavanaugh agreed to participate in a hearing under oath, chaired by the senate judiciary committee, to determine mr kavanaugh’s suitability for his nomination, based on the conduct reported by dr ford. 
in a courageous and dignified testimony, dr ford presented her account of the events that occurred in 1982. she was challenged by some critics as to why she could recall some details but not others; however, this is consistent with memory recall of people who have experienced trauma. despite a groundswell of support rallying behind dr ford, and the prominence of the #metoo , #believesurvivors ,  and #timesup campaigns, mr kavanaugh was appointed chief justice of the supreme court. since then, however, dr ford has endured continued harassment, necessitating personal security measures, and she has been unable to resume her professorial duties at palo alto. 
the experience of dr ford has created an important public dialogue the impacts a person’s decision to report sexual violence (or not). despite bearing all the hallmarks of a ‘good victim’, such as being educated, intelligent, married; she was still disbelieved. these events highlight the importance of community education around the impacts and incidence of sexual assault.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate™ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
något som gör mig stolt över att arbeta för sida i georgien är att sverige ses som en så betydelsefull och pålitlig förespråkare inom jämställdhet. på konferensen som jag och mina kollegor från ambassaden deltar i idag, beskrevs sverige som den mest engagerade partnern inom jämställdhet i georgien.
.
den här veckan uppmärksammas #16daysofactivism against gender-based violence och det är vad som diskuteras på konferensen. våld mot kvinnor och flickor och sexuella trakasserier är ett stort problem i georgien och lagstiftning mot sexuella trakasserier saknas. men det går framåt.
.
#metoo -rörelsen har inte varit lika stor i georgien som i sverige, men har ändå bidragit till en ökad politisk vilja att ta fram lagar för att främja jämställdhet samt förebygga och straffa våld mot kvinnor och flickor. trots många skillnader mellan georgien och sverige har jag upptäckt många likheter vad gäller jämställdhet. kampen fortsätter! 💪 /theodora

#enannanbild #jämställdhet

text:
day 5 of 16 days activism 
silence, directed by fiona compton 
silence is a film made in conjunction with not asking for it - a campaign aimed at stopping abuse against women. touching on the knock on effect of child abuse into adulthood, 'silence' is an emotional insight into abusive relationships.
written by spoken word poet curmiah lisette - this film was a collaboration with not asking for it founder fiona compton to provide a rarely seen perspective on abuse.
for more of our 16 days 16 films campaign, please visit the link in bio! #16days16films #whaticando
